# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1991-nba-finals
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] The **1947 BAA Finals** was the championship round of playoffs following the inaugural Basketball Association of America (BAA)'s 1946–47 season.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] The Philadelphia Warriors of the Eastern Division faced the Chicago Stags of the Western Division for the inaugural championship, with Philadelphia having home court advantage.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Hall of Fame inductee Joe Fulks played for the Warriors in the series.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Philadelphia was not the Eastern Division champion but advanced to the championship round by winning a four-team playoff among the Eastern and Western Division runners-up.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Meanwhile, the Eastern and Western Division champions, Washington Capitols and Chicago Stags, played one long series to determine the other finalist, a best-of-seven series that Chicago won 4–2.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] In the runners-up bracket, Philadelphia and New York from the East had first eliminated St.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Louis and Cleveland from the West, then faced each other, all in best-of-three series.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] The format was repeated in 1948, and generated another champion from the runners-up bracket.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] The five games of the final series were played in seven days, with no days off between consecutive games in the same city (twice).
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Division champions Washington and Chicago had played the six games of their semifinal series from April 2 to 13, although they too took no days off between consecutive games in the same city (twice).
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] In total, the entire playoff tournament lasted a total of 20 days.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] This would be the Stags only appearance in the Finals; the franchise would fold three years later.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] It would be another 44 years before a Chicago club played for a pro basketball championship, when the Chicago Bulls won the 1991 NBA Finals.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Joe Fulks then scored 29 points in the second half, including 21 in the fourth quarter.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Angelo Musi, a guard out of Temple University, scored 19 points himself for Philadelphia as well.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] The Stags took an astounding 129 shots, but only knocked down 26 of them, a 20.2 shooting percentage which made it easy for the Warriors to win, 84–71.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Fulks was not the scorer he was in Game 1, but he did not have to be, because five other Warrior players scored in double figures, including 18 points from forward Howie Dallmar and 16 from guard Jerry Fleishman.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] Chicago did take a brief 69–68 lead until Philadelphia center Art Hillhouse came alive in the fourth quarter.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] He scored 7 out of the last 10 points for the Warriors, in route to a second Philadelphia win, 85–74.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] The Stags staved off elimination and avoided a sweep with a one-point victory.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1947-baa-finals] With less than a minute remaining, Howie Dallmar snapped an 80–80 tie by nailing a jump shot to seal the very first championship for the Warriors.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] The **1948 BAA Finals** was the championship round of the Basketball Association of America's 1947–48 season.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] The defending 1947 BAA champions Philadelphia Warriors of the Eastern Division faced the Baltimore Bullets of the Western Division, with Philadelphia having home court advantage.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] This was the first professional sports championship ever won by a Baltimore-based team.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] Baltimore was not the Western Division champion but advanced to the championship round by winning a four-team playoff among the Eastern and Western Division runners-up.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] Meanwhile, the Eastern and Western Division champions, Philadelphia Warriors and St.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] Louis Bombers, played one long series to determine the other finalist, a best-of-seven series that Philadelphia won 4–3.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] In the runners-up bracket, Baltimore and Chicago from the West had first eliminated New York and Boston from the East, then faced each other in a best-of-three series.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] The format was used only twice, in 1947 and 1948, and generated two champions from the runners-up bracket.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] The six games of the final series were played in *twelve* days, with at least one day off except prior to the decisive game.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] Louis had played the seven games of their semifinal series in *fifteen* days, March 23 to April 6, with at least one day off before every game.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] The entire playoff tournament extended 30 days.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-baa-finals] As of 2023, this is the only BAA/NBA Finals which a now-defunct team won (as opposed to teams that changed names and/or moved to other cities in later years).
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The **1948 Globetrotters–Lakers game** was a dramatic match-up between the Harlem Globetrotters and the Minneapolis Lakers.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Played in Chicago Stadium, the game took place two years before professional basketball was desegregated.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The Globetrotters' 61–59 victory – by two points at the buzzer – challenged prevailing racial stereotypes about the abilities of black athletes.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The idea for the game, which was held on February 19, 1948, was hatched by Globetrotters owner and coach Abe Saperstein and Lakers general manager Max Winter, two friends who both believed they had the best basketball team in the country.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] For two decades, the Globetrotters had traveled the country winning game after game.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] It was because the team was so unbeatable that the players first started clowning around to make the game more interesting.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] When the Globetrotters arrived at the Chicago Stadium to face the Lakers, they were on a 102-game winning streak.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] As a black team, the Globetrotters were not allowed into the NBL or the BAA.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] A year earlier, Jackie Robinson had broken the color barrier in professional baseball, but basketball remained segregated.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Four black basketball players had briefly been on various teams in another league, the National Basketball League.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] But when a fight between a white player and a black player during a game in Syracuse, New York, triggered a riot in the stands, black players quietly disappeared from the league.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Many sports fans, team owners, and coaches did not want to see teams integrated.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Some held the racist view that blacks were not equipped for sports like basketball that required coordination, strategy, and finesse.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] In 1941, Dean Cromwell, the assistant head coach for the U.S. track team at the 1936 Summer Olympics, which included Jesse Owens, wrote that black athletes excelled in certain events because they were closer to primitive man than white men were.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Racism dominated other aspects of the Globetrotters' lives as well.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The night before the game, the team checked into the same small two-story rooming house on the segregated South Side of Chicago that they visited every time they were in town.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Called Ma Piersall's, its rooms were tiny, no more than ten feet by ten feet, and featured sagging single beds.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Across town, the Lakers spent the night at the popular, luxurious, high-rise Morrison Hotel where a month earlier a black actress had been denied a room and told to find a room in a "South Side hotel for colored people".
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] A record number of fans showed up at Chicago Stadium to watch the Lakers face off against the Globetrotters.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] It was an exhibition game played right before the official Basketball Association of America contest between the Chicago Stags and the New York Knicks.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Still in its infancy, professional basketball had never attracted more than 9,000 fans in Chicago.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] That day, nearly 18,000 filled the stadium.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The Globetrotters starting lineup, a combination of the best players from Saperstein's East and West units that toured both the United States of America and the rest of the world, featured Reece "Goose" Tatum, Marques Haynes, Ermer Robinson, Wilbert King, and Louis "Babe" Pressley.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] During the first half, Laker fans had reason to gloat.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Their team quickly jumped to a 9–2 lead.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The Lakers held a significant height advantage over the Globetrotters, with several players towering over Tatum, the Globetrotters' star, six-foot-three center, and Haynes, who was barely six feet tall.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Tatum turned out to be no match for Mikan, the Lakers' center, who scored 18 points in the first half while preventing Tatum from scoring at all.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] During the break, Saperstein and his team devised a plan to defend Mikan with two men instead of one.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] They also decided to do fast break plays each time they got the ball in order to quickly tire the Lakers out during the second half.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The Globetrotters knew they were in great shape, having played nearly every night for as long as they could remember.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] With both Tatum and Pressley guarding Mikan, he was able to score only 6 points in the second half.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The Globetrotters tied the game for the first time in the third quarter.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] On several occasions they led, only to watch the Lakers come back to tie the score.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] In the final quarter, both Tatum and Pressley fouled out from guarding Mikan so closely.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The rest of the team picked up the slack.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] With 90 seconds left, the Lakers tied the game at 59 with a free throw.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] When the Globetrotters got the ball, Marques Haynes, who earlier in the game had teased the Lakers by dribbling while lying down on the court, dribbled to run out the clock, since there was no shot clock at the time.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] This was easy for Haynes: He once dribbled an entire fourth quarter to overcome a two-player handicap and sustain the Globetrotters' one-point lead.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] With only a few seconds left, Haynes flipped the ball to Ermer Robinson, who was stationed 30 feet from the basket.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Flexing his knees and holding the ball to his chest, Robinson let fly the one-handed shot he had practiced hundreds of times a day on his childhood courts in San Diego.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] It was the same shot he had already missed three times in a row, and he hadn't sunk any from that far out.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] When the Globetrotters reached their locker room, they hoisted Saperstein, who was wearing double-breasted suit and wide tie, onto their shoulders.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] A year later, the Lakers and Globetrotters met for a rematch, with the Globetrotters again winning, this time 49–45.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The teams met six more times after that, with the Lakers winning each of those games.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The racial implications of the game were not immediately apparent.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The *Chicago Sun-Times*' headline, "Mikan Cooks Tatum's Goose", focused on the fact that the Globetrotter star only scored three baskets.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Neither Saperstein nor Winter saw the game as being about race relations; they simply wanted to see which team was best.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] "I'm positive that he [Abe] didn't see it as a racial game", Gerald Saperstein, a cousin of Abe Saperstein's who was at the game, told the Associated Press.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] But to many team owners in the young and struggling basketball leagues, there was a clear message: Not only were black players as talented and capable as white players, they added a level of excitement to the game that appealed to both white and black audiences.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] To black basketball fans, it was a moment of empowerment.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] "It just revitalized so many of us, from the fact that [it showed] what we can be", said John Chaney, the former longtime Temple University basketball coach who, in 1948, was a teenager in deeply segregated Jacksonville, Florida.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Two years later, in 1950, three former Globetrotters became the first black players on NBA teams.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The Boston Celtics drafted Chuck Cooper, the New York Knicks signed center Nat "Sweetwater" Clifton, and the Tri-Cities Blackhawks (now the Atlanta Hawks) took Hank DeZonie.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] As basketball became integrated, giving talented black players greater opportunity to play professionally, the Globetrotters had fewer recruits to choose from.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Rather than try to compete with the NBA, Abe Saperstein transformed the Globetrotters into a touring act, first against teams of all-star college players around the country and then with ambitious tours of Europe, South America, and the rest of the world.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The Globetrotters also expanded their dazzling ball handling and shooting tricks, cementing their reputation as "the magicians of basketball".
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The Lakers went on to become an outstanding team, winning six professional basketball titles in the next seven years: 1948 (NBL), 1949 (BAA), 1950 (NBA), 1952 (NBA), 1953 (NBA), 1954 (NBA).
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] When Mikan retired in 1954, the team struggled financially.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] To boost attendance and revenue, then-owner Bob Short relocated the team to Los Angeles before the 1960–61 season.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Chicago Stadium, the venue of the first Globetrotter-Lakers game, was demolished in 1995.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] The impact of that game, however, was felt for many years to come.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] "Those Lakers-Trotters games definitely contributed to the integration of the league", basketball historian Claude Johnson told ESPN.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] Stan Bergstein worked for the Globetrotters as announcer and promotions at the time.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1948-globetrotters-lakers-game] From his personal collection of photos, this is Marques Haynes, George Mikan, Stan Bergstein and Goose Tatum taken the day of the game.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] The **1949 BAA Finals** was the championship round following the Basketball Association of America (BAA)'s 1948–49 season, its third and last.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] Later that year, the BAA and National Basketball League merged to create the National Basketball Association (NBA).
[src:1991-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] 6'10" George Mikan and the Minneapolis Lakers proved dominant.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] They routed the Washington Capitols in six games.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] This was the first of several successive NBA titles for the Lakers.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] It was the beginning of the George Mikan and the Lakers Dynasty.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] This was the first professional sports championship ever won by a Minneapolis-St.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] The six games of the final series were played in ten days – Monday, April 4, to Wednesday, April 13 – with one day off except after game three, the first of three played in Washington (Minneapolis led 3–0).
[src:1991-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] Prior to its start, however, Minneapolis had been idle for five days, having qualified on the preceding Tuesday; Washington idle for only one day, having qualified on Saturday.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1949-baa-finals] The entire playoff tournament extended 23 days.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] The **1950 NBA World Championship Series** was the championship round of the National Basketball Association (NBA)'s inaugural 1949–50 season following the merger of the National Basketball League (NBL) and the Basketball Association of America (BAA).
[src:1991-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] The defending 1949 BAA champions and Central Division champions Minneapolis Lakers faced the Eastern Division champion Syracuse Nationals in a best-of-seven series with Syracuse having home-court advantage.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] In the event, six games were played in 16 days, beginning Saturday and Sunday, April 8 and 9, in Syracuse and incorporating two subsequent Sunday games in Minneapolis.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] Counting a Central Division tiebreaker played on Monday, March 20, the entire postseason tournament spanned five full weeks to Sunday, April 23.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] The NBA was arranged in three divisions (for its first season only) and the first two rounds of the 1950 NBA playoffs generated three Division champions.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] With the league's best regular season record, Syracuse had earned a place in the Finals by winning the Eastern Division title on the preceding Sunday, and had been five days idle while the Central and Western champions had played a best-of-three series mid-week.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] In Game 1, the Lakers won on a buzzer beating shot by sub Bob "Tiger" Harrison, the first known case of a buzzer beater in the Finals.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] Six-foot-eight-inch (2.03 m) Dolph Schayes of Syracuse led his team out to the finals after a 16.8 ppg average during the regular season.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] George Mikan, however, averaged 27.4 ppg and led the league.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] Mikan would lead the Lakers past Syracuse in six games.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] The championship was the Lakers third professional championship in a row after winning the NBL championship in 1948 and the BAA championship in 1949.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1950-nba-finals] While the NBA was considered a new league at the time, it later retconned the three preceding BAA seasons as part of its own history, and thus presents the 1950 Finals as its fourth championship series.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The **1951 NBA World Championship Series** was the championship round of the 1951 NBA playoffs, which concluded the National Basketball Association 1950–51 season.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] It featured an all-New York matchup Western Division champion Rochester Royals faced the Eastern Division champion New York Knickerbockers in a best-of-seven series with Rochester having home-court advantage.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] This was the only time the NBA Finals ever featured two teams from the same state.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] Rochester won the first three games, two at home, but New York won the next three, two at home.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] It was the first BAA or NBA Finals (spanning 1947 to 1951) that extended to a seventh-game conclusion, a 4-point win by Rochester at home on Saturday, April 21.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The seven games were played in fifteen days, beginning Saturday and Sunday, April 7 and 8, in Rochester and incorporating one game in Rochester on each following weekend.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] Three Wednesday or Friday games were played in New York City.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The entire postseason tournament spanned 33 days in which both Rochester and New York played 14 games.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The Royals appeared in their first NBA finals by defeating the Fort Wayne Pistons in the semifinals and the two-time defending champion Minneapolis Lakers in the division finals while the Knickerbockers defeated the Boston Celtics in the semifinals and the Syracuse Nationals in the division finals.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] This was the first finals appearance for both teams, and the first Finals with two teams that had not made a finals appearance since the 1947 BAA Finals.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The Rochester / Cincinnati Royals / Kansas City / Sacramento Kings won their first ever NBA Championship.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The Knickerbockers led 74–72 with under three minutes later but Arnie Risen and Bob Davies (who combined for 44 points scored in the game) managed to draw quick shots and free throws in the final minutes to give the Royals a 79–75 victory.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] Contrary to today's practices, there was no trophy presentation or a parade.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] This was the first and to date last title for the Rochester Royals, who would move to Cincinnati, Ohio for the 1958 season.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The Royals would spend 15 years mired in mediocrity before moving to Kansas City, Missouri in 1972, changing their name in the process to the Kings.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] One notable highlight was their appearance in the 1981 NBA playoffs, in which their 40–42 team reached the Western Conference finals before losing to the Houston Rockets, who also had a 40–42 record.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The Kings moved to Sacramento, California in 1985, where they have remained to this day.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The team reached the Western Conference finals in 2002, where they lost in seven games to the Los Angeles Lakers in a highly controversial series.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The Kings’ 2002 Western Conference final run was the closest the team got to reaching the NBA Finals in the modern era.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] The Royals/Kings have the longest NBA title drought, the longest NBA Finals appearance drought, the longest active championship round appearance drought in all four of the American major pro sports leagues, and the third longest championship drought in North American sports.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] This would be the Knickerbockers' first of three consecutive appearances in the Finals, but they would lose all three times.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1951-nba-finals] They would not return to the Finals until 1970, which they won.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] The **1952 NBA World Championship Series** was the championship round of the 1952 NBA playoffs, which concluded the National Basketball Association (NBA)'s 1951–52 season.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] The Western Division champion Minneapolis Lakers faced the Eastern Division champion New York Knickerbockers in a best-of-seven series with Minneapolis having home-court advantage.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] Minneapolis won game one and the teams thereafter alternated victories, Minneapolis winning the decisive game by a 17-point margin at home on Friday, April 25.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] All but Game 7 were played in the teams' secondary arenas: the Lakers played at the Saint Paul Auditorium, while the Barnum circus bumped the Knickerbockers from Madison Square Garden to the 69th Regiment Armory.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] The seven games were played in fourteen days, beginning Saturday and Sunday, April 12 and 13, in Minneapolis/St.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] Paul for games five and seven on the following Saturday and Friday.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] Meanwhile, three Wednesday or Friday games were played in New York City.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] The entire postseason tournament spanned 39 days in which Minneapolis played 13 games and New York 14.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1952-nba-finals] This was the first playoff meeting between these two teams.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The **1991 NBA Finals** was the championship series of the National Basketball Association's (NBA) 1990–91 season, and the conclusion of the season's playoffs.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] It was also the first NBA Finals broadcast by NBC after 17 years with CBS.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Eastern Conference champion Chicago Bulls took on the Western Conference champion Los Angeles Lakers for the title, with Chicago having home court advantage.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] It was Michael Jordan's first NBA Finals appearance, Magic Johnson's last, and the last NBA Finals for the Lakers until 2000.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Jordan averaged 31.2 points on 56% shooting, 11.4 assists, 6.6 rebounds, 2.8 steals and 1.4 blocks en route to his first NBA Finals MVP Award.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The series was not the first time that the Bulls and Lakers faced off in the playoffs.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Prior to 1991, they met for four postseason series (1968, 1971, 1972 and 1973), all Lakers victories.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Chicago was a member of the Western Conference at the time and moved into the East in 1980.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The 1991 Finals marked the first time the Bulls defeated the Lakers in a playoff series.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] This series would mark the end of the Lakers Showtime era and the beginning of the Bulls' dynasty.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] After winning five championships in eight finals appearances in the 1980s, the Lakers would enter a period of mediocrity for most of the 1990s before winning five championships between the 2000 and 2010 seasons.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The 1991 Lakers were led by Johnson, who was 31 and playing in what would be his last full season, as well as fellow All-Star teammate James Worthy; Kareem Abdul-Jabbar had retired two seasons earlier.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Bulls, led by Jordan and small forward Scottie Pippen, would win five more championships after 1991 in a seven-year span, cementing their status as a dynasty.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Jordan became only the fourth player in NBA history (after Joe Fulks, George Mikan, and Abdul-Jabbar) to capture the scoring title and a championship in the same season.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] This was the first meeting between teams from Chicago and Los Angeles for a major professional sports championship since the 1959 World Series.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The 1990–91 season marked the Bulls' 25th in franchise history.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The team was coming off a grueling seven-game loss to the Detroit Pistons in the 1990 Eastern Conference finals, and in the six years since Michael Jordan joined the Bulls, they were showing signs of improvement.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] They managed to put it all together that season, winning a then-franchise record 61 games.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Jordan won the scoring title for a fifth consecutive season, but the team was no longer a one-man show of years past.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Instead, Jordan distributed the ball with regularity, thanks in large part to the triangle offense instituted by head coach Phil Jackson and assistant Tex Winter.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] This gave the Bulls additional offensive weapons to choose from, ranging from wingman Scottie Pippen and post players Horace Grant and Bill Cartwright to shooters such as John Paxson and B.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Jordan's improved all-around play earned him his second MVP award.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] In the playoffs, the Bulls lost only once in the first three rounds.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] They swept the New York Knicks in the first round, then eliminated the Philadelphia 76ers in the second round.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Their much-awaited rematch with the Detroit Pistons in the Conference finals showcased the maturity and poise that the Bulls displayed all season, as they swept the Pistons.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] In a last show of defiance, most of the Pistons walked off the court with :08 left on the clock in a blowout loss at home so as not to congratulate the new Eastern Conference champions, though Joe Dumars, Vinnie Johnson, and John Salley did remain to shake the Bulls' hands.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Lakers were coming off a second-round loss to the Phoenix Suns in prior season's playoffs.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Even though the Lakers won 63 games that season, and Magic Johnson was second in league MVP voting while surpassing Oscar Robertson for the all-time career assist record, it was clear that the team was growing weary of head coach Pat Riley's intense approach.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Lakers replaced Riley with Mike Dunleavy, Sr., formerly an assistant coach with the Milwaukee Bucks.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Dunleavy then abandoned the trademark Showtime offense in favor of a more deliberate style of play, but despite the change in playbook, the Lakers still enjoyed an impressive season, winning 58 games.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] In the playoffs, the Lakers swept the Houston Rockets in the first round, then eliminated Run TMC and the Golden State Warriors in the second round.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Next up for the Lakers were the Portland Trail Blazers, who were coming off a trip to the NBA finals the previous year.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Lakers stunned the Blazers in Portland to open the series, and went on to win the conference finals in six games.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Michael Jordan started dominating with 15 points, 3 rebounds and 5 assists in the first quarter alone.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] In the second quarter, the Lakers continued to stay competitive despite Magic Johnson not attempting one field goal in the second quarter.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Despite this, Johnson would hit back-to-back 3 pointers in the third quarter to give the Lakers their largest lead, and also Johnson's 29th career playoff triple-double.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Jordan made a comeback in the fourth quarter with 13 points, but it was Scottie Pippen's two free throws that would give the Bulls a 91–89 lead.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Each team ran the shot clock down but neither could hit a shot until Sam Perkins hit a 3-pointer (the potential game winner) with 14 seconds left to give the Lakers a 92–91 lead.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Jordan's 17-foot jumper then rattled out and was rebounded by Byron Scott, who was fouled with 2.7 seconds remaining.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Scott missed the first of his two free throws and made the second for a 93–91 Lakers lead.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Bulls, out of timeouts, had a final chance, but a midcourt heave from Pippen at the buzzer caromed off the back of the rim.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] This was also the last time any game of the NBA Finals aired in the afternoon (Eastern Time Zone), with every game of the NBA Finals since this game in 1991 airing in prime time, including all weekend games.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] To date, this is the most recent time any finals game in any of the four major American sports leagues started before 6:00 p.m.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] after Jordan's 13th straight point on a mid-air, switch-handed layup.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] This would be one of Albert's most iconic calls.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The biggest decision of the game was putting Scottie Pippen on Magic Johnson, while Michael Jordan guarded Vlade Divac and also switched to the point guard position for the rest of the series.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] This would go on to be one of the most memorable plays in NBA Finals history.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Lakers were in the game even when Chicago was leading 58–51 until Byron Scott fouled Pippen, and the Bulls would make 17 of their next 20 field goals in the third quarter despite Jordan spending time on the bench with foul trouble.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] By the time Jordan returned, their lead was 16 and then Jordan led the Bulls to an 11–0 run to a Bulls victory.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Bulls were having trouble in the frontcourt (in Game 1, the Lakers frontcourt outscored Chicago's 60–31).
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] In Game 3, the Lakers would be the ones having trouble, setting a rebounding low in the Finals.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Despite this problem, the Lakers went for an 18–2 run that brought them from 3 down (49–52) to 13 up (67–54).
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Bulls would answer with a 20–7 run that would tie the game in the 4th quarter at 74.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Horace Grant's layup gave the Bulls a 90–87 lead with 1:07 to play.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Perkins then scored to cut the Bulls' lead to 90–89 with 49 seconds left.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] After a Bulls' miss, Divac scored on a layup and was fouled.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] He made the free throw to give the Lakers a 92–90 lead with 10.9 seconds remaining.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Jordan made a 14-foot jump shot just inches away from Divac's fingertips with 3.4 seconds left to tie the game at 92 and force overtime.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] In overtime, Jordan would score half of the Bulls' 12 points to win the game.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Lakers had a 28–27 lead in the first quarter; only the second time in the 1991 playoffs that a team led the Bulls at the end of the first quarter.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] This did not matter as Chicago went on a 19–9 run to start the second period and gain a 46–37 lead.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] While Michael Jordan scored 11 points in the second quarter, the Lakers only made 12 of their 41 shots in the second and third quarters.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Lakers faced a huge blow as Worthy and Scott left the game (and eventually the series) with ankle and shoulder injuries, respectively (Worthy's ankle injury from the Conference finals against Portland had flared up, and Scott injured his shoulder after slipping on a wet spot on the floor).
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] With the lack of Worthy and Scott, and bad shooting (especially from Sam Perkins), the Bulls were able to take a 16-point lead in the third quarter.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Lakers refused to go down and shrank the deficit to 7 points in the fourth quarter, but it was the closest they would get, as Pippen and Jordan led the Bulls on a 19–8 run to put them one game away from their first NBA Championship.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Lakers were facing elimination, and the absences of James Worthy and Byron Scott increased the difficulty for the Lakers.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] This would not stop Magic Johnson who added 20 assists and 11 rebounds.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Jordan guarded Magic Johnson in Game 5 which led Magic to struggle by scoring 16 points on 33% (4/12) shooting with 6 turnovers.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Elden Campbell outscored Michael Jordan with 13 points in the first half.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Lakers still fought and even led 93–90 in the fourth quarter, but the Bulls went on a 9–0 run, and Paxson's 10 points in the final half of the fourth quarter helped secure the Chicago Bulls', and Jordan's, first NBA title.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] It was the only one of the Bulls' six Finals appearances to end in four games to one.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] This was also the last NBA Finals game to be played in The Forum (by the time the Lakers returned to the NBA Finals, they had moved to the new Staples Center).
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Scottie Pippen led the Bulls with 32 points and collected 13 rebounds.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Jordan, who was named the Finals MVP, added 30 points and 10 assists.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] This was the first Finals to be telecast in the United States by NBC.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] NBC Sports used Marv Albert on play-by-play and Mike Fratello as color analyst.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Ahmad Rashad (for the Bulls) and Steve "Snapper" Jones (for the Lakers) served as sideline reporters.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] This was the only NBA Finals series in which recently departed Lakers coach Pat Riley worked as a broadcaster; he was paired with Bob Costas in the pre-game, half-time and post-game presentations.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Riley was then hired as head coach by the New York Knicks in the 1991 offseason and would eventually win another title with the Miami Heat in 2006.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] In Chicago, this was Jim Durham's only Finals appearance as the Bulls' radio announcer (he also announced Bulls games on television via simulcast during the regular season and playoffs).
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] He would later announce several NBA Finals games on ESPN Radio.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Neil Funk succeeded Durham the following season and was the radio voice on five NBA Finals involving the Bulls (1992, 1993, 1996, 1997 and 1998).
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The simulcasts would also end after the season, with Wayne Larrivee (on WGN-TV) and Tom Dore (on cable) becoming the Bulls' television announcers the next season; by the 2008–09 NBA season Funk was calling television play-by-play on both networks while Chuck Swirsky called radio play-by-play.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] This was also the only NBA Finals to feature Johnny Kerr on color commentary, as he would become exclusive to television after the Finals.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] During the Bulls White House visit in 1991, guard Craig Hodges wore a dashiki and delivered a letter to President George H.W.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Bush criticizing his administration's treatment of minorities and the poor.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Hodges believed this act of activism, along with his outspokenness, led to him being blackballed from the NBA shortly after in 1992.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Bulls’ victory in the 1991 Finals started a dynasty that lasted until 1998.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] They continued their dominance over the NBA the next year, as they knocked off the Portland Trail Blazers in six games to repeat as champions.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Lakers' Showtime era would end on November 7, 1991, as Magic Johnson announced his retirement due to the HIV virus.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] He did, however, play in the 1992 NBA All-Star Game and eventually with the Dream Team in the 1992 Summer Olympics.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Lakers would decline in the years following Magic's retirement, being eliminated in the first round of the playoffs two straight years (1992 – 1993) before missing the playoffs entirely in 1994.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] The Lakers would eventually return to the Finals in 2000, knocking off the Reggie Miller-led Indiana Pacers in six games, which marked the start of a new dynasty for the franchise led by stars Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Many of the Showtime era would stick around in the organizations after their playing careers were done.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Norm Nixon and Kurt Rambis, players not on the 1991 Finals team but recognizable from their Showtime era days, also took jobs in and around the organization.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Nixon was studio color analyst for all Lakers home games for Fox Sports West for a number of years.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Rambis had a short-lived stint as head coach in 1999, was an assistant coach throughout multiple stints over 15 years, and senior basketball adviser in the front office since 2018.
[src:1991-nba-finals/1991-nba-finals] Phil Jackson would later coach to Lakers from 1999 to 2004 and 2005 to 2011 after the Bulls dynasty ran its course in 1998, leading the Lakers to five championships over the course of those two stints.
